    flow:uploadTimestamp "2025-11-09T08:03:28.894080+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    dcterms:description "The resource is a transcribed dialogue that dramatizes the arrival of a new high‑school basketball coach, Ken Carter, and his efforts to impose discipline, academic standards, and a winning mindset on a struggling team. The conversation weaves together interactions between the coach, school administrators, players, and a parent, highlighting the coach’s emphasis on contracts that require a minimum 2.3 GPA, class attendance, and front‑row seating, as well as a rigorous conditioning regimen. Throughout the exchange, Carter stresses that success on the court is linked to personal responsibility and academic achievement, promising that “the losing stops now.” The script also captures the tension and resistance from some players, who question the coach’s authority and react with sarcasm and hostility. Administrative figures discuss logistical details such as a stipend and coffee orders, while the coach repeatedly asserts his credentials and expectations. Overall, the piece illustrates themes of mentorship, accountability, and the challenges of transforming a low‑performing sports program within an under‑resourced school environment." ;
    dcterms:title "Coach_Carter___Full_Movie___LOL!_Throwbacks(480p).mp4" .

<http://flow_ai.org/ontology#video/I_Have_a_Dream_speech_by_Martin_Luther_King__Jr_HD__subtitled__360p__20251107T091521Z_f62740> a flow:VideoFile ;
    flow:chunkCount 1 ;
    flow:embeddingModel "sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2" ;
    flow:embeddingStatus "completed" ;
    flow:fileFormat "video" ;
    flow:fileSizeMB 1.789e+01 ;
    flow:namespace "I_Have_a_Dream_speech_by_Martin_Luther_King__Jr_HD__subtitled__360p__20251107T091521Z_f62740" ;
    flow:uploadTimestamp "2025-11-07T09:15:21.454734+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    dcterms:description "The resource presents a rendition of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.’s historic “I Have a Dream” address, delivered during the 1963 March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom. It opens by referencing the Emancipation Proclamation and the centennial legacy of slavery, then moves into King’s vision of a nation where racial injustice is eliminated. Central themes include the call for equality, the aspiration that people be judged by “the content of their character,” and the hope for reconciliation between descendants of enslaved people and former slave owners. The text repeatedly invokes the metaphor of a “dream” to describe a future in which segregation, poverty, and discrimination are replaced by freedom, brotherhood, and justice across all states—from Mississippi to New Hampshire. It also emphasizes collective action, faith, and non‑violent protest as means to achieve this transformation. While the passage contains numerous transcription errors and unconventional phrasing, it retains the core message of King’s appeal for civil rights, unity, and moral progress in America." ;
    dcterms:title "I_Have_a_Dream_speech_by_Martin_Luther_King_.Jr_HD__subtitled_(360p).mp4" .

<http://flow_ai.org/ontology#video/Linked_Lists_-_Singly___Doubly_Linked_-_DSA_Course_in_Python_Lecture_3_720p__20251108T172531Z_a9d607> a flow:VideoFile ;
    flow:chunkCount 5 ;
    flow:embeddingModel "sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2" ;
    flow:embeddingStatus "completed" ;
    flow:fileFormat "video" ;
    flow:fileSizeMB 2.897e+01 ;
    flow:namespace "Linked_Lists_-_Singly___Doubly_Linked_-_DSA_Course_in_Python_Lecture_3_720p__20251108T172531Z_a9d607" ;
    flow:uploadTimestamp "2025-11-08T17:25:31.496762+00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    dcterms:description "The resource is an informal tutorial that introduces the concept of linked lists, focusing on singly linked lists and briefly mentioning doubly linked lists. It explains that a singly linked list consists of nodes—objects that contain a value and a reference (or “next” pointer) to the subsequent node—forming a chain that terminates with a special marker such as null (None in Python). Unlike arrays, linked lists do not store elements in contiguous memory and lack direct index access; instead, operations start from a reference to the head node and require traversal to locate a particular element. The discussion covers how nodes are represented in programming languages using classes and objects, the role of memory addresses, and the distinction between linked lists and arrays in terms of data retrieval. It also outlines basic manipulations: inserting a new node at a given position and deleting a node, both of which involve traversing from the head and updating pointer references, with a time complexity of O(n). The tutorial emphasizes that while the examples use simple numeric values, any data type can be stored in a linked‑list node." ;
    dcterms:title "Linked_Lists_-_Singly___Doubly_Linked_-_DSA_Course_in_Python_Lecture_3(720p).mp4" .

